# valgrind.supp — Valgrind Memcheck suppressions for the nginx-xrootd harness.
#
# NATIVE VALGRIND SYNTAX — this is NOT the ASan/LSan `leak:<substr>` format used
# in tests/lsan.supp. The two files are not interchangeable.
#
# RULE (same as lsan.supp): suppress ONLY benign nginx-core-startup / library
# one-time residuals. NEVER suppress a leak whose stack contains a module frame
# (brix_*, ngx_http_brix_*, ngx_stream_brix_*, or any src/<module>/ file).
# Suppressions match from the TOP of the stack, so deliberately list the full
# distinctive frame chain — do NOT write a blanket `obj:*/libcrypto.so*` leak
# rule: it would also hide a real module leak that merely allocates via OpenSSL
# (exactly how the Phase 27 JWKS EVP_PKEY leak presented).
#
# We run with `--show-leak-kinds=definite,indirect`, so library "still reachable"
# globals never appear and need no suppression here. Regenerate additions with
# `valgrind --gen-suppressions=all` and hand-trim to the benign set.

# nginx core: one-time copy of the environment block at startup (nginx.c).
{
   nginx-core-ngx_set_environment
   Memcheck:Leak
   match-leak-kinds: definite
   fun:malloc
   fun:ngx_alloc
   fun:ngx_set_environment
}

# glibc/pthread allocator thread-local arena bookkeeping reported as "possibly
# lost" at exit. Matched by the libc/ld frame chain only — never by module code.
{
   libc-pthread-threadlocal-possible
   Memcheck:Leak
   match-leak-kinds: possible
   ...
   fun:_dl_allocate_tls
   ...
}
{
   libc-allocate-specific-possible
   Memcheck:Leak
   match-leak-kinds: possible
   ...
   fun:allocate_dtv
   ...
}
